In the [[philosophy]] of [[consciousness]], the '''anti-nesting principle''' states that one [[state of consciousness]] cannot exist within another.<ref name=Kammerer2015>{{Cite journal|title = How a Materialist Can Deny That the United States is Probably Conscious – Response to Schwitzgebel|journal = Philosophia|volume = 43|issue = 4|date = 2015-09-28|issn = 0048-3893|pages = 1047–1057|doi = 10.1007/s11406-015-9653-z|language = en|first = François|last = Kammerer}}</ref>

Proponents of the anti-nesting principle include [[Giulio Tononi]]<ref>{{Cite journal|title = If materialism is true, the United States is probably conscious|journal = Philosophical Studies|date = 2014-10-08|issn = 0031-8116|pages = 1697–1721|volume = 172|issue = 7|doi = 10.1007/s11098-014-0387-8|language = en|first = Eric|last = Schwitzgebel|citeseerx = 10.1.1.694.59}}</ref> and [[Hilary Putnam]].<ref name=Kammerer2015/>

